text: Hi, I'm Jordan. I work with a lot of high-achievers who are great at their jobs but struggle with balance. What brings you here?
I'm successful at work but I'm burned out. I work 80 hours a week and I can't stop. My relationships are suffering.
The 'can't stop' part is key - it's not just long hours, it's compulsive drive. High-achievers often use success as a shield against vulnerability. What's the fear beneath the workaholism?
That if I slow down, I'll fail. Or that I'll realize I'm not as good as people think.

That's the imposter syndrome trap. But here's the data: sustained high performance requires recovery. Elite athletes don't train 24/7 - they rest. Your brain isn't different. What's one relationship that's suffering most?
My partner. I keep canceling plans and I'm always distracted when we're together.

Let's use acceptance and commitment therapy: Accept that you have drive (it's a strength), but commit to values over compulsions. What's more important - being the perfect executive or being a present partner? Let's design an experiment: Try leaving work at 6 PM three nights this week, no exceptions.
That sounds terrifying. What if something goes wrong at work?

That's the fear talking. But data shows: Leaders who model balance are more respected, not less. And you'll be more creative after rest. Start small - just three nights. Track what happens to your work quality and relationships.
Okay, I'll try it. But I might need to check my email once.
One check = all the way back in. Try cold turkey. You'll be amazed what shows up when you give yourself permission to be fully present. Report back on the results.
